Service types. Cluster eye-pee, node port, load balancer, and external name.

A service's type field controls how reachable it is. There are four values, and each is mostly a superset of the one before.

Cluster eye-pee is the default. The service gets a virtual address from the service range, and it is reachable only from inside the cluster. This is what every internal microservice should be.

Node port makes the service reachable on every node's address, at a port in the thirty thousand range. It includes a cluster eye-pee too. From outside, you would hit any node's address on that node port. Use it for development clusters, and for bare metal clusters without a load balancer. In a real cloud cluster, you almost never expose a node port directly. A load balancer or an ingress sits in front.

Load balancer exposes the service through a cloud provided external load balancer, and it implies a node port too. The cloud controller manager talks to the cloud ay-pee-eye, provisions the load balancer, and writes its public address back into the status. On kind and minikube there is no cloud provider, so these services stay pending forever, unless a tool like metal-el-bee plugs in a fake one.

External name is a different beast. No proxying, no selector, no endpoints. It is just a dee-en-ess see-name, from the service name to an external hostname. Pods that look up the service get that external hostname back. It is useful for giving an external dependency a kubernetes shaped name, so client manifests look the same in every environment.

On our map, all four are the same service chip, just dialed to different reach. The internal virtual address is the base, and each higher type simply adds an outward door.
